              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24392685#p24392685" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Crombie</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24389803#p24389803" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Mannymal</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Official moderation notice.<br /><br /><br />Hey guys, I don't want to play book vs. series police. But this thread is clearly marked for discussion of events and characters are portrayed in the series to date. While the briefest of mention above of someone's preference for a character's portrayal in the series over their portrayal in the books obviously can't be considered a spoiler, <span style="font-style: italic"><span style="font-weight: bold">I think it's appropriate to remind everyone that--for the purposes of this particular thread--the books may as well not exist.</span></span> Please restrict discussion to the events and characters portrayed in the series to date. There's another thread for the combined discussion of both the book and television series.</div><br /><br />I think if you guys stick to the bolded part no one will have problems with you. You dont have to go back and delete anything.<br /><br />Just out of politeness, guys. Even if you are not spoiling anything, the TV people dont even like reading your comments if they know you read the books. <br /><br />Me? I think its too much trouble, so I dont even participate.</div><br /><br />You do not even have any skin in the game, and would not be able to participate in either thread. So, why does your opinion matter?</div><br />You're, of course, free to question whether our opinion matters to the question at hand, but there <span style="font-style: italic">are</span> those of us non-subs who like to poke our head over the paywall to read what others who share our interests think about the stuff we're watching. Often it leads to much <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/sad.png" alt=":(" title="Frown" /> as we realize that the thing we like isn't popular (up to and including serious tear-downs of every little problem) but in some cases, as with GoT (and JonBob's Farscape thread), it leads to some interesting reading from others who are enjoying the show.<br /><br />To me, if something is said/shown on the show and leaves a detail ambiguous to a show-only watcher it should stay ambiguous. Just because it was made obvious in the book doesn't mean that it wasn't left ambiguous on the show for no reason. The internet let out a collective gasp in 1x08 when something they thought would never happen did. On reflection of previous episodes the indication that things were going to go the way they did was there, but left either undirected or non-obvious. <span style="font-style: italic">Specifically</span> so they could have that moment later in the season. That can, and probably <span style="font-style: italic">will</span>, happen more as the show goes on.<br /><br />Unless you're a showrunner or writer no book reader knows more about <span style="font-style: italic">how</span> they're going to get to any of the upcoming plot points than those of us who only watch the show. Those little tidbits that don't matter so much (possibly like <div style="padding: 3px;">
  <div style="margin-bottom: 3px; font-weight: bold;" onclick="var q = $(this).parent().find('.quotecontent > div');q.toggle();$(this).find('span').html(q.is(':visible')?'hide':'show');return false;">
    <b>Spoiler: </b>
    <span style="color: #FF5B00; cursor: pointer;">show</span>
  </div>
  <div class="quotecontent">
    <div style="display: none;">
      how Jaime doesn&#39;t lie
    </div>
  </div>
</div>) to someone who already knows the overall arc of the story <span style="font-style: italic">can</span> mean a lot, or mean nothing at all. It isn't up to <span style="font-style: italic">you</span> to make that determination though.

              

              
              
            </div>
